before_start: {"blocks":[{"key":"bijq5","text":"In order to protect the individuals from the potential HepB virus infection while working with human blood, the U.S.A. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) issued a recommendation for HepB vaccination to be carried out in individuals before they start working with human blood. Vaccine-induced antibody titer to the HepB virus of ≥10 mIU/mL should be present in individuals before commencing work with human blood.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":108,"length":83}],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"C9AE6BE043E011ED9F6DC515692A38AB","url":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/rr6210a1.htm"}}}}
description: {"blocks":[{"key":"6b68g","text":"Vitamin K antagonists are anticoagulants which represent widely prescribed drugs for prevention and treatment of thromboembolic disorders. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bic7u","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"eptrb","text":"The molecular target of these drugs is vitamin K epoxide reductase enzyme and their metabolism is performed by the cytochrome P-450 2C9 enzyme, both of which are encoded by polymorphic genes - vitamin K epoxide reductase complex subunit 1 (VKORC1) and cytochrome P-450 2C9 (CYP2C9), respectively. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":240,"length":6},{"style":"italic","offset":274,"length":6}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cqvk5","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"33d16","text":"Identification of VKORC1 and CYP2C9 genotypes was recommended by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration in 2007, in order to guide the initial dosing of warfarin, the first oral vitamin K antagonist drug, to achieve optimum anticoagulation and prevent hemorrhagic events. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":18,"length":6},{"style":"italic","offset":29,"length":6}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a8nod","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cndra","text":"This protocol is designed for undergraduate students of pharmacology or medicine, or anyone receiving training in pharmacogenomics/pharmacogenetics and understanding a relationship between a gene and drug response for the first time. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3i7v0","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cpd34","text":"The protocol represents a step-by-step guide to using polymerase chain reaction restriction fragment length polymorphism (PCR-RFLP) method in determining VKORC1 -1639G\u003eA, CYP2C9*1/*1, CYP2C9*1/*2, CYP2C9*1/*3, and CYP2C9*2/*3 genotypes. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":154,"length":15},{"style":"italic","offset":171,"length":11},{"style":"italic","offset":184,"length":11},{"style":"italic","offset":197,"length":11},{"style":"italic","offset":214,"length":11}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4dvgq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cb1","text":"Based on the combination of the VKORC1 -1639G\u003eA and CYP2C9 genotypes, that is, the pattern of DNA fragments, which are visualized using agarose gel electrophoresis and DNA staining, a conclusion on an individual’s sensitivity to vitamin K antagonists and appropriate drug dose is reached. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":32,"length":15},{"style":"italic","offset":52,"length":6}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"243m3","text":"Patients' whole blood was collected in ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (EDTA)-containing tubes and stored at -20°C until use. Genomic DNA extraction from the human whole blood, that is, leukocytes, was carried out according to the protocol described by Subbarayan PR and colleagues (doi: 10.2144/02336bm10), with modifications. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":253,"length":28}],"data":{}},{"key":"5spbj","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"csj0t","text":"Upon thawing of the blood, for every patient's blood sample, five (5) sterile tubes were labeled and 300 μl of the whole blood was added.
